- VSCode Version: 1.2.1
- OS Version: Win 7 Pro

create a `file.ts` with code:

```
let item = "value1";
let элемент = "value2";
```

In VSCode you'll see it this way:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7231941/16284980/894737aa-38dc-11e6-8001-398d4730168d.png)

The identifier `item` has blue color, but `элемент` is white. In the first line the string value is brown, but in the second line the coloring is corrupted completely.

The same happens with everithing: function names, class names, class member names etc. For example:

```
function Main_Функция(s: string)
{
}

function Функция_Main(s: string)
{
}
```

This code looks like this:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7231941/16285331/30c65fe6-38de-11e6-9b54-ddccf61ac500.png)

- VSCode Version: 1.3.0-insider; commit a6aa320
- OS Version: Windows 8.1

When separately applying a decoration and an :after decoration to the same range of text, moving the cursor around will cause the former decoration to appear and disappear on all but the last character of the range. The effect is subtly dependent on the existence of lines of text elsewhere in the document; the bigger the document the more noticeable the bug gets.

I have not seen this bug with the :before decoration yet.

see: #7181

MWE:

``` typescript
  const dec1 = vscode.window.createTextEditorDecorationType({
    textDecoration: "line-through",
  });
  const dec2 = vscode.window.createTextEditorDecorationType({
    after: { contentText: "$$$" }
  });
    function lineRange(line, start, end) { return new vscode.Range(line,start,line,end) }
  const editor = vscode.window.activeTextEditor;
  if (editor) {
    const lines = [
      "--- some-text --- (no decoration)",
      "--- some-text --- (line-through)",
      "--- some-text --- (line-through & :after)",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "aaaaaa",
            "END OF EXAMPLE", "", "", ]
    editor.edit((edit) => {
      edit.insert(new vscode.Position(0,0), lines.join('\n'));
    }).then(() => {
      editor.setDecorations(dec1, [lineRange(1,4,13), lineRange(2,4,13)]);
      editor.setDecorations(dec2, [lineRange(2,4,13)]);
    });
  }
```

